His three boats stove around him, and oars and men both whirling in the eddies; one captain, seizing the line-knifeline-knife: also called "boat-knife" (see glossary) kept in the bow of the whaleboat for cutting the whale line in an emergency. from his broken prow, had dashed at the whale, as an Arkansas duellistArkansas duellist: Frontier knife-fighter; Melville alludes to the predominantly southern “tall tale” tradition of early American humor (1830–1860) featuring such real and imaginary frontier braggarts and belligerents as Davy Crockett and T. B. Thorpe’s Jim Doggett in “The Big Bear of Arkansas.” at his foe, blindly seeking with a six inch blade to reach the fathom-deep life of the whale. That captain was Ahab. And then it was that suddenly sweeping his sickle-shaped lower jaw beneath him, Moby Dick had reaped away Ahab’s leg, as a mower a blade of grass in the field. No turbaned Turk, no hired Venetian or Malay, could have smote him with more seeming malice. Small reason was there to doubt, then, that ever since that almost fatal encounter, Ahab had cherished a wild vindictiveness against the whale, all the more
fellfell: fierce; cruel. for that in his frantic morbidness he at last came to identify with him, not only all his bodily woes, but all his intellectual and spiritual exasperations. The White Whale swam before him as the monomaniacmonomaniac: obsessed with one subject. incarnation of all those malicious agencies which some deep men feel eating in them, till they are left living on with half a heart and half a lung. That intangible malignity which has been from the beginning; to whose dominion even the modern Christians ascribe one-half of the worldsREVISION NARRATIVE: to whose dominion even the modern Christians ascribe one-half of the worlds // The reference is to Manichaeism, a third-century doctrine derived from Persian, Gnostic, and Christian thinking that divides existence into good and evil. Augustine adopted but later renounced it in the fourth century. It became prevalent in thirteenth-century southern France, where it was brutally repressed. Melville’s claim that “modern Christians” subscribe to the kind of Manichean dualism projected here is arguably excessive, and the British edition removed it. To compare American and British pages, click the thumbnails in the right margin.;
which the ancient OphitesOphites: Early dualistic Christian sect that reverenced the liberating serpent, enemy of the Hebrew Bible’s God. of the east reverenced in their statue devil;—Ahab did not fall down and worship it like them; but deliriously transferring its idea to the abhorred white whale, he pitted himself, all mutilated, against it. All that most maddens and torments; all that stirs up the lees of things; all truth with malice in it; all that cracks the sinews and cakes the brain; all the subtle demonisms of life and thought; all evil, to crazy Ahab, were visibly personified, and made practically assailable in Moby Dick. He piled upon the whale’s white hump the sum of all the general rage and hate felt by his whole race from Adam down; and then, as if his chest had been a mortar, he burst his hot heart’s shell upon it.
